<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="note">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
The nominal subgenus is quite readily diagnosed, as the first flagellomere has a narrow, produced point on the anterodorsal corner and the lateral scutellar setae are absent. The point on the first flagellomere is sometimes reduced so that the segment has only a slight anterodorsal angle (
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.4039/Ent134577-5" author="Boucher, S" journalOrPublisher="The Canadian Entomologist" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="577 - 603" refId="B10" refString="Boucher, S, 2002. Revision of Nearctic species of Cerodontha (Cerodontha) (Diptera: Agromyzidae). The Canadian Entomologist 134: 577 - 603, DOI: https://doi.org/10.4039/Ent134577-5" title="Revision of Nearctic species of Cerodontha (Cerodontha) (Diptera: Agromyzidae)." url="https://doi.org/10.4039/Ent134577-5" volume="134" year="2002">Boucher 2002</bibRefCitation>
). The habitus is also quite characteristic, with species being relatively slender and elongate, and often quite heavily marked with yellow. The 
<taxonomicName authority="Xenophytomyza" class="Insecta" family="Phytomyzinae" genus="Cerodontha" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="(Xenophytomyza) subsp. subgenus" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subGenus" species="angulata" subGenus="Xenophytomyza" subSpecies="subgenus">subgenus Xenophytomyza</taxonomicName>
is similar in that the lateral scutellars are also absent and the first flagellomere is angled, but this angle is slight, never produced as a point, and the body is entirely dark, never with yellow markings.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
The subgenus contains ca. 60 species, with the ten Nearctic species revised by 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.4039/Ent134577-5" author="Boucher, S" journalOrPublisher="The Canadian Entomologist" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="577 - 603" refId="B10" refString="Boucher, S, 2002. Revision of Nearctic species of Cerodontha (Cerodontha) (Diptera: Agromyzidae). The Canadian Entomologist 134: 577 - 603, DOI: https://doi.org/10.4039/Ent134577-5" title="Revision of Nearctic species of Cerodontha (Cerodontha) (Diptera: Agromyzidae)." url="https://doi.org/10.4039/Ent134577-5" volume="134" year="2002">Boucher (2002)</bibRefCitation>
. The widespread and morphologically variable species 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" genus="C." higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="C. dorsalis" order="Asterales" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="dorsalis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">C. dorsalis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Loew) occurs in the Delmarva states.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
